<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2014-11-24T10:52:54-07:00</updated>
<published>2014-11-24T10:52:54-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12059&amp;p=136867#p136867</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12059&amp;p=136867#p136867"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Electrical componets on NES boards]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12059&amp;p=136867#p136867"><![CDATA[
Integrated circuits need <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decoupling_capacitor" class="postlink">bypass capacitors</a> to even out the power supply during times of high current consumption. When an IC switches a lot of gates at once, it uses more current, and the cap kicks out some of its stored energy to keep the power pin at an even 5 V above ground. (The cap recharges during idle time when the IC isn't using quite as much current.) There should usually be a 10-22 μF or so electrolytic or tantalum cap near the power pins of the edge connector, plus a 100 nF ceramic cap next to the Vcc pin of each IC. Usually for the smaller ICs (7400 series) you can get away with sharing the cap with another IC.<br /><br />I'm guessing that if older revisions of NES Game Pak PCBs lacked capacitors, later revisions had them to improve reliability under load. They sure fixed <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?p=104980#p104980" class="postlink">magno's board</a>.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon Nov 24, 2014 10:52 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
